  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Safety filters in text-to-image systems are not a single mechanism but a stack of checkpoints applied at different stages of generation. They range from blocklist-based prompt rejection to CLIP-based output classifiers to weight-level concept erasure, each with different coverage, cost, and failure modes. Understanding how each works, where it sits in the pipeline, and what it misses is essential for building responsible production systems and for knowing when and how to configure them appropriately for your context."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Where Safety Filters Sit"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A production text-to-image system has three distinct intervention points. Prompt-level filters run before any generation compute is spent. Model-level interventions (concept erasure) are baked into the weights at fine-tune time. Output-level classifiers run on the decoded image after generation. Each handles a different threat and each can fail independently."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Text-to-image safety filter pipeline showing prompt filter, CLIP text encoder, U-Net denoiser with optional concept erasure, VAE decoder, NSFW classifier, and blocked vs safe output paths"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Stable Diffusion Safety Checker"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The default Stable Diffusion v1.x and v2.x safety checker uses CLIP to measure the cosine similarity between the decoded output image and a fixed set of \"unsafe concept\" embeddings. The embeddings were derived from captions and image descriptions of the content categories the authors wanted to suppress. If any similarity score exceeds a threshold, the pipeline replaces the output with a black image."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# How the diffusers safety checker is applied (simplified from the source)\n\nfrom diffusers.pipelines.stable_diffusion.safety_checker import StableDiffusionSafetyChecker\nfrom transformers import CLIPFeatureExtractor\nimport torch, numpy as np\nfrom PIL import Image\n\nsafety_checker   = StableDiffusionSafetyChecker.from_pretrained(\"CompVis/stable-diffusion-safety-checker\")\nfeature_extractor = CLIPFeatureExtractor.from_pretrained(\"openai/clip-vit-base-patch32\")\n\ndef check_image(pil_image: Image.Image) -> tuple[Image.Image, bool]:\n    \"\"\"Returns (image_or_black, has_nsfw_concept).\"\"\"\n    # Convert to a feature tensor the CLIP model expects\n    safety_inputs = feature_extractor(images=[pil_image], return_tensors=\"pt\")\n    # Run the checker (it returns the image and a bool list per image in batch)\n    checked_images, has_nsfw = safety_checker(\n        images=[np.array(pil_image) / 255.0],   # float [0,1]\n        clip_input=safety_inputs.pixel_values,\n    )\n    if has_nsfw[0]:\n        return Image.fromarray(np.zeros_like(np.array(pil_image), dtype=np.uint8)), True\n    return pil_image, False\n\n# In the diffusers pipeline this is called automatically after decode:\n# output = pipe(prompt=\"...\")   # safety_checker applied inside\n# output.nsfw_content_detected  # list[bool], one per image in the batch"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The CLIP-based checker has well-documented weaknesses. Because it operates on the full decoded image via a fixed concept embedding, it can be fooled by style transfer, low-resolution images, or unusual color palettes that shift the CLIP embedding away from the threshold. It also produces false positives on legitimate medical and artistic content that occupies the same CLIP regions as unsafe concepts."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Configuring the Safety Checker"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Diffusers exposes the safety checker as a swappable component. You can disable it entirely for research contexts, replace it with a custom classifier, or raise/lower the threshold by modifying the checker's internal concept embeddings."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from diffusers import StableDiffusionPipeline\nimport torch\n\n# Option 1: disable the safety checker entirely (research/medical contexts)\npipe = StableDiffusionPipeline.from_pretrained(\n    \"runwayml/stable-diffusion-v1-5\",\n    safety_checker=None,          # no checker loaded\n    requires_safety_checker=False,\n    torch_dtype=torch.float16,\n).to(\"cuda\")\n\n# Option 2: replace with a custom binary classifier\nclass CustomSafetyChecker:\n    def __init__(self, model, threshold=0.5):\n        self.model = model\n        self.threshold = threshold\n\n    def __call__(self, images, clip_input, **kwargs):\n        \"\"\"Must return (images, has_nsfw_list).\"\"\"\n        import numpy as np\n        has_nsfw = []\n        black = np.zeros_like(images[0], dtype=np.uint8)\n        out_images = []\n        for img in images:\n            score = self.model.predict(img.reshape(1, -1))[0]\n            is_nsfw = float(score) > self.threshold\n            has_nsfw.append(is_nsfw)\n            out_images.append(black if is_nsfw else img)\n        return out_images, has_nsfw\n\n# Option 3: raise false-positive tolerance by inspecting concept scores before threshold\n# (requires patching the checker internals — see StableDiffusionSafetyChecker.forward)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prompt-Level Filtering"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prompt filtering rejects requests before generation starts, saving compute and providing a first line of defence against adversarial inputs. The simplest approach is a keyword blocklist. More robust approaches run the prompt through a text classifier trained to detect harmful intent, or use an embedding-space threshold against known problematic prompt clusters."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Layered prompt filter: blocklist + embedding-space check\n\nimport re\nfrom transformers import CLIPTokenizer, CLIPTextModel\nimport torch\n\n# --- Layer 1: keyword blocklist ---\nBLOCKLIST = re.compile(\n    r\"\\b(nsfw|explicit|nude|naked|violence|gore|harm)\\b\",\n    re.IGNORECASE,\n)\n\ndef blocklist_filter(prompt: str) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Returns True if safe.\"\"\"\n    return not BLOCKLIST.search(prompt)\n\n# --- Layer 2: embedding similarity against known-bad anchor prompts ---\ntokenizer  = CLIPTokenizer.from_pretrained(\"openai/clip-vit-large-patch14\")\ntext_model = CLIPTextModel.from_pretrained(\"openai/clip-vit-large-patch14\").eval()\n\ndef embed(text: str) -> torch.Tensor:\n    t = tokenizer(text, return_tensors=\"pt\", max_length=77, truncation=True, padding=\"max_length\")\n    with torch.no_grad():\n        e = text_model(**t).pooler_output\n    return e / e.norm(dim=-1, keepdim=True)\n\n# Pre-compute anchor embeddings of known-harmful intent descriptions\nANCHORS = [\n    \"explicit sexual content\",\n    \"graphic violence and gore\",\n    \"child exploitation material\",\n]\nanchor_embs = torch.cat([embed(a) for a in ANCHORS], dim=0)  # (3, 768)\n\nSIMILARITY_THRESHOLD = 0.28  # tune on a labelled eval set\n\ndef embedding_filter(prompt: str) -> bool:\n    \"\"\"Returns True if safe.\"\"\"\n    p_emb = embed(prompt)                         # (1, 768)\n    sims  = (p_emb @ anchor_embs.T).squeeze(0)   # (3,)\n    return sims.max().item() < SIMILARITY_THRESHOLD\n\ndef is_prompt_safe(prompt: str) -> bool:\n    return blocklist_filter(prompt) and embedding_filter(prompt)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Concept Erasure (ESD)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Erased Stable Diffusion (ESD) modifies the model weights to make certain concepts ungeneratable regardless of the prompt. Unlike output-level filters, concept erasure cannot be bypassed by adversarial prompts — the model literally cannot produce the erased concept because the relevant directions in its feature space have been suppressed. The technique fine-tunes the U-Net's cross-attention weights to predict the same noise for a target concept as it would for an empty prompt."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\mathcal{L}_{\\text{ESD}} = \\mathbb{E}_{x_t, t}\\left[\\left\\| \\varepsilon_\\theta(x_t, t, c_{\\text{target}}) - \\varepsilon_{\\theta^*}(x_t, t, \\varnothing) \\right\\|^2\\right]"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Where ",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "θ*",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the frozen original model and ",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "θ",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the model being fine-tuned. The fine-tuning pushes the cross-attention weights to produce the unconditioned denoising trajectory whenever the target concept appears in the prompt, regardless of how the concept is phrased."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# ESD concept erasure training loop (simplified — cross-attention weights only)\n\nimport torch, torch.nn.functional as F\nfrom diffusers import StableDiffusionPipeline, DDPMScheduler\n\ndef erase_concept(model_id: str, concept: str, steps: int = 500, lr: float = 1e-5):\n    pipe = StableDiffusionPipeline.from_pretrained(model_id, torch_dtype=torch.float32)\n    pipe = pipe.to(\"cuda\")\n    scheduler = DDPMScheduler.from_config(pipe.scheduler.config)\n\n    # Freeze everything except cross-attention projections in the U-Net\n    for name, param in pipe.unet.named_parameters():\n        param.requires_grad = \"attn2\" in name   # cross-attention layers only\n\n    opt = torch.optim.AdamW(\n        [p for p in pipe.unet.parameters() if p.requires_grad], lr=lr\n    )\n\n    pipe.unet.train()\n    for step in range(steps):\n        # Sample a latent from the frozen model conditioned on the concept\n        with torch.no_grad():\n            concept_emb = pipe._encode_prompt(concept, \"cuda\", 1, False)\n            empty_emb   = pipe._encode_prompt(\"\",      \"cuda\", 1, False)\n            x = torch.randn(1, 4, 64, 64, device=\"cuda\")\n            t = torch.randint(0, scheduler.num_train_timesteps, (1,), device=\"cuda\")\n            noise = torch.randn_like(x)\n            x_noisy = scheduler.add_noise(x, noise, t)\n\n            # Target: what the FROZEN model predicts for empty prompt\n            target = pipe.unet(x_noisy, t, encoder_hidden_states=empty_emb).sample\n\n        # Train model to predict the same noise when conditioned on the concept\n        pred = pipe.unet(x_noisy, t, encoder_hidden_states=concept_emb).sample\n        loss = F.mse_loss(pred, target)\n\n        opt.zero_grad()\n        loss.backward()\n        opt.step()\n\n        if step % 100 == 0:\n            print(f\"Step {step}: loss={loss.item():.4f}\")\n\n    return pipe   # erased model — save with pipe.save_pretrained(...)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Safe Latent Diffusion"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Safe Latent Diffusion (SLD) modifies the denoising update at inference time rather than modifying the weights. At each step, an additional safety guidance term is subtracted from the noise prediction whenever the latent's current trajectory is heading toward an unsafe region. SLD does not require retraining and applies without any external classifier — it re-uses the model's own semantic understanding."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\hat{\\varepsilon} = \\varepsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, c_{\\text{pos}}) - \\lambda_s \\left(\\varepsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, c_{\\text{pos}}) - \\varepsilon_{\\theta}(x_t, c_{\\text{unsafe}})\\right)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The safety guidance scale ",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "λs",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " controls how strongly the update is repelled from unsafe regions. SLD is available in diffusers as a drop-in pipeline replacement:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from diffusers import StableDiffusionPipelineSafe\nimport torch\n\n# SLD adds three extra parameters to every sampling call\npipe = StableDiffusionPipelineSafe.from_pretrained(\n    \"AIML-TUDA/stable-diffusion-safe\",\n    torch_dtype=torch.float16,\n).to(\"cuda\")\n\nimage = pipe(\n    prompt=\"a painting of a forest at night\",\n    # SLD guidance parameters:\n    sld_guidance_scale=1000,   # strength of safety repulsion (0 = disabled)\n    sld_warmup_steps=10,       # steps before SLD activates (let content form first)\n    sld_threshold=0.01,        # only apply when unsafe score exceeds this\n    sld_momentum_scale=0.5,    # momentum for smoothing the safety update\n    sld_mom_beta=0.7,          # EMA decay for momentum\n    # Standard params:\n    num_inference_steps=30,\n    guidance_scale=7.5,\n    generator=torch.Generator(\"cuda\").manual_seed(0),\n).images[0]\n\n# SLD does not black-out images — it redirects generation to a safe alternative.\n# Unlike output filters, it can produce a meaningful image even when the\n# original prompt pointed toward unsafe content."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Production Safety Stacks"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A production system combines multiple layers because no single filter is sufficient. The depth-in-defence approach applies each layer in order of cost:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "attrs": {
          "start": 1
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
